      rationale: "This patient is experiencing postpartum hemorrhage (PPH), the leading cause of maternal death worldwide. The most common cause is uterine ATONY (failure of the uterus to contract after delivery), accounting for ~80% of PPH cases. Risk factors include: macrosomic baby (9 lbs), overdistended uterus, prolonged labor, and multiparity. The BOGGY uterus (soft, not firm) confirms atony. The uterus displaced to the RIGHT suggests a full bladder pushing the uterus off midline and preventing effective contraction. Immediate management follows the mnemonic 'TAMPONADE': (1) Tone - MASSAGE the fundus vigorously with one hand while the other supports the lower uterine segment to stimulate myometrial contraction; (2) have the patient VOID or insert a catheter to empty the bladder (a full bladder prevents the uterus from contracting); (3) administer OXYTOCIN (Pitocin) IV drip to strengthen uterine contractions; if oxytocin is insufficient, additional uterotonics include methylergonovine (Methergine - contraindicated in hypertension), carboprost (Hemabate - contraindicated in asthma), and misoprostol (Cytotec); (4) monitor vital signs for shock; (5) maintain IV access with large-bore catheter; (6) monitor and quantify blood loss; (7) prepare for possible surgical intervention if medical management fails.",
