      rationale: "Cushing's triad (also called Cushing's response or reflex) is a set of three vital sign changes that indicate CRITICALLY elevated intracranial pressure with impending brain herniation. It is a LATE and OMINOUS sign: (1) HYPERTENSION with WIDENING PULSE PRESSURE (BP 180/90 = pulse pressure of 90 mmHg; normal is 30-40 mmHg): the brain attempts to maintain cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP = MAP - ICP) by dramatically increasing systemic blood pressure through massive sympathetic stimulation. As ICP rises, higher MAP is needed to push blood into the brain; (2) BRADYCARDIA (HR 52): the baroreceptors in the aortic arch and carotid sinuses detect the severe hypertension and trigger a parasympathetic (vagal) response to slow the heart rate; (3) IRREGULAR RESPIRATIONS: pressure on the brainstem respiratory centers causes abnormal breathing patterns (Cheyne-Stokes, central neurogenic hyperventilation, ataxic/Biot's breathing, or apnea). This triad indicates that compensatory mechanisms are FAILING and brain herniation is imminent. The RN must: immediately notify the neurosurgeon, prepare for possible emergent surgical intervention (craniotomy, ventriculostomy), administer osmotic diuretics (mannitol) or hypertonic saline as ordered, elevate the head of bed to 30 degrees, maintain the head in midline position, and avoid any activities that increase ICP (coughing, straining, suctioning).",
