      rationale: "Addisonian crisis (acute adrenal crisis) is a life-threatening emergency occurring in patients with adrenal insufficiency (Addison disease) when they experience physiological stress (surgery, dental procedures, infection, trauma) without adequate glucocorticoid replacement. Addison disease involves destruction of the adrenal cortex, resulting in deficiency of: CORTISOL (glucocorticoid - essential for stress response, blood pressure maintenance, glucose regulation) and ALDOSTERONE (mineralocorticoid - regulates sodium/potassium balance and blood volume). During physiological stress, the normal adrenal glands dramatically increase cortisol production (up to 10x normal). Patients with Addison disease cannot mount this response, leading to: SEVERE HYPOTENSION from loss of cortisol's permissive effect on catecholamines and aldosterone-mediated sodium/water loss; TACHYCARDIA as compensatory response; HYPOGLYCEMIA from loss of cortisol's gluconeogenic effect; SEVERE ABDOMINAL PAIN, nausea, and vomiting. Treatment is IMMEDIATE: (1) IV HYDROCORTISONE 100 mg bolus then 50-100 mg every 8 hours (replaces both cortisol and has mineralocorticoid activity at high doses); (2) AGGRESSIVE IV FLUID resuscitation with 0.9% NS and D5W; (3) GLUCOSE correction; (4) electrolyte monitoring and correction; (5) identify and treat the precipitating stressor. Prevention: patients with Addison disease must be taught to INCREASE their steroid dose ('stress dosing') during illness, surgery, or dental procedures.",
