      rationale: "Large-volume paracentesis (LVP) - removal of >5 liters of ascitic fluid - carries a significant risk of post-paracentesis circulatory dysfunction (PPCD). The pathophysiology: when large volumes of ascitic fluid are rapidly removed, the sudden decrease in intra-abdominal pressure causes splanchnic vasodilation and redistribution of blood volume. Additionally, removing protein-rich ascitic fluid creates an oncotic gradient that draws plasma from the intravascular space into the peritoneal cavity, further depleting intravascular volume. This results in: HYPOTENSION (decreased blood return to the heart), ACTIVATION of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (leading to sodium/water retention and rapid ascites re-accumulation), and potential HEPATORENAL SYNDROME (acute kidney injury from decreased renal perfusion). To prevent PPCD, guidelines recommend: ALBUMIN INFUSION (6-8 g of albumin per liter of fluid removed beyond 5 L) to maintain intravascular oncotic pressure. The RN must: monitor vital signs every 15 minutes during the procedure and frequently after, assess for signs of hypovolemia (tachycardia, hypotension, dizziness), measure abdominal girth before and after, record the volume and characteristics of the fluid removed, send fluid samples for analysis (cell count, albumin, culture), and monitor renal function.",
